My thoughts on the term â€œChinese New Yearâ€: * 1) We are discussing the use of an English phrase to say Happy New Year to some ethnicities celebrating the festivity, so calling it Chinese New Year is definitely not inclusive.  * 2) If people like to get scientific, they might call it â€œSino Luni-Solar New Yearâ€, but then where is the fun and the feel when things are too serious and over-scientific haha * 3) Historically sppeaking, the term Chinese New Year has been commonly used in Western countries to reflect the reality of the Chinese settlement in these places. But, itâ€™s the 21st century now when the world has never been more multicultural locally. Hence, the time has come for the term to be retired for good.  * 4) Thereâ€™s no right or wrong here since the Chinese people donâ€™t say â€œHappy Chinese New Yearâ€ to each others, and neither do the Vietnamese people say â€œHappy Tetâ€ to each others. * 5) So, it comes down to choosing an English phrase that is both reflecting the very multicultural reality that we are living in AND being mindful of all ethnicities and different peoplesâ€™ feeling.  * 6) My Chinese-background friends and I have both been very comfortable using the term â€œHappy Lunar New Yearâ€ since we joined the same English class in Australia back in 2008 thanks to our Teacher. * 7) Many of you here are teachers of English and/or great English users, and itâ€™s our responsibility to spread the word on this matter like The USâ€™s First Lady Jill Biden has been doing for decades now. You can tell how great of an English Teacher and how compassionate of an individual she is from the video below. # Itâ€™s time for a change, and change for the better.  #HappyLunarNewYear
